== Old English ==
=== Etymology ===
From Germanic ''*wurmi-'', from a suffixed form of Indo-European ''*wer-'' ‘turn, bend’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[wirm]], Old Saxon [[wurm]] (Dutch [[worm]]), Old High German [[wurm]] (German [[Wurm]]), Old Norse [[ormr]] (Swedish [[orm]] ‘serpent’), Gothic [[𐍅𐌰𐌿𐍂𐌼𐍃]] ‘worm, serpent’.  The IE root is also the source of Latin [[vermis]] ‘worm’, Lithuanian [[varmas]] ‘midge’, Old Russian ''vermije'' ‘locusts, worms’, Greek [[ῥόμος]] (originally *ϝράμος) ‘earthworm’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /wyrm/

=== Noun ===
'''wyrm''' ''m'' (''pl'' '''wyrmas''')

# a [[serpent]] or [[snake]]
